header.gameNote: SAN ANTONIO REGIONAL AT DENVER CO

article.description:
Candice Wiggins popped out for 3-pointers, pulled 
up for jumpers and weaved through the lane for layups.
article.headline: Wiggins leads Stanford past Missouri State
article.linkText: Wiggins leads Stanford past Missouri State
article.story:
DENVER (AP) -- Stanford played stifling defense, got a solid game
from its best player and rested its starters down the stretch.

OK, so it was a little sloppy at times, but an easy victory sure
was a great way to kick off the NCAA Tournament.

Candice Wiggins picked apart Southeast Missouri State's defense
for 21 points and Stanford dominated the lane at both ends, helping
the Cardinal roll to a 72-45 victory Saturday night in the San
Antonio Regional.

Other than 17 turnovers and a few bad shots that made coach Tara
VanDerveer cringe, Stanford (24-7) played like a third seed should
against a 14, putting the game away early and emptying its bench
late to move on to Monday's second round against Florida State.

"It was great for us to win our first game in the NCAA
tournament because if you don't, they are none after that,"
VanDerveer said.

The Cardinal has appeared in the NCAA tournament 19 straight
times and reached the second round seven of the last eight years,
including the last four. Stanford won NCAA championships in 1990
and 1992, reached the Final Four six times in the 1990s and has had
a winning record in 27 of its 32 seasons.

Southeast Missouri State (22-9) had never won a conference title
before this season, making its first NCAA tournament appearance
this year by beating Tennessee Tech in the Ohio Valley Conference
championship to get an automatic bid.

The difference in the programs was apparent from the tip.

Stanford's Kristen Newlin and Brooke Smith dominated inside,
blocking and altering shots at one end, powering through the paint
for easy baskets at the other. Smith finished with 14 points, nine
rebounds and three blocked shots, helping Stanford to a 40-8
advantage inside.

In case that wasn't enough, Wiggins darted and dashed her way
through the Redhawks' defense with relative ease, scoring 13
first-half points on a variety of layups, runners and jumpers. The
Pac-10's player of the year finished 8-for-15 and had six rebounds.

"She really hurt us off the dribble drives," Southeast
Missouri State coach B.J. Smith said. "The tough thing about her
is she doesn't a weakness. If you really help too much, she hits
people for open shots. If you get too tight on her, she'll blow by
you, and she's got great size and finishes so well at the basket.
And then she shoots it so well. So we struggled."

The Cardinal opened the game with a 13-4 run, let Southeast
Missouri State pull within five, then steamrolled the Redhawks with
a 15-3 run to take a 37-24 lead by halftime. The Cardinal did it
mostly on talent because they sure had VanDerveer shaking her head
with all the bad passes and poor shot selection.

"That did have me go ballistic," VanDerveer said. "There were
times I asked myself what were we doing and who was out there in
those uniforms."

Defense wasn't a problem, though.

Stanford harassed Southeast Missouri State into missing 23 of
its 29 shots in the first half, holding the Redhawks without a
field goal for one 14-minute stretch. Southeast Missouri State
certainly helped, taking bad shots and missing good ones, including
a breakaway layup by Katrisha Dunn midway through the first half,
to shoot 21 percent.

"We knew who their shooters were and who were their drivers,"
Brooke Smith said. "Maybe we forced them to shoot shots they
didn't necessarily want to take. We stuck to the plan and it worked
well for us."

The Redhawks did manage to chip Stanford's lead down to 37-29 in
the first two minutes of the second half, but couldn't get any
closer. Wiggins had seven points during a 13-0 run after that,
capping it with a 3-pointer that put the Cardinal up 50-29.

Natalie Purcell led Southeast Missouri State with 17 points.

"We put on our thumbprint on Southeast Missouri and made
history for doing this for the first time," Redhawks guard
Tiffanie Ryan said. "Of course, we're disappointed in our show
today. But we know we had a good season."
